issue_body:
 We encounter query performance degrade after we upgrade to 7.12. The performance is almost 2 times slower than old version.
Below is the flame graph after in 7.12
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1617828/112288804-ac7aaa00-8cc8-11eb-902f-c8d78951b379.png)

You can see `BytesReferenceStreamInput.maybeNextSlice` may be the performance bottleneck now and it is introduced in https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/pull/65921.

The query is 
```
{
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "filter": [
        {
          "terms": {
            "xxxx_id": [
              xxxxx
              ]
          }
        },
        {
          "range": {
            "local_stat_time_hour": {
              "lt": "2020-12-30 00:00:00",
              "gte": "2020-10-01 00:00:00",
              "time_zone": "+00:00"
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "aggs": {
    "stat_time_hour": {
      "date_histogram": {
        "min_doc_count": 1,
        "format": "yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss",
        "interval": "hour",
        "extended_bounds": {
          "max": "2020-12-30 00:00:00",
          "min": "2020-10-01 00:00:00"
        },
        "field": "local_stat_time_hour"
      },
      "aggs": {
        "campaign_id": {
          "terms": {
            "field": "zzz_id",
            "size": 50000,
            "min_doc_count": 1
          },
          "aggs": {
            "yyyy": {
              "sum": {
                "field": "yyyy"
              }
            },
     ............... total 92 sum aggs
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "size": 0
}
```

In 7.6.2, it takes 15 seconds to run the query but in 7.12, it takes 30 seconds. The response size is 600MB.
I guess if we can construct a query which produce large response size and many sum aggs, then we can reproduce the issue.

**Elasticsearch** 7.10.2 - 7.12.0

**Plugins installed**: []

**JVM version** (`java -version`): openjdk 11.0.10 2021-01-19

**OS version** Ubuntu 20.10

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
When using profile=true in REST requests, global sub aggregation results seem to be scoped by the query

**Steps to reproduce**:

```
PUT /test/_doc/1
{
  "aField": "A"
}

PUT /test/_doc/2
{
  "aField": "B"
}

PUT /test/_doc/3
{
  "aField": "B"
}

POST /test/_search
{
  "profile": "true", 
  "size":0,
  "query": {
    "term": {
      "aField.keyword": {
        "value": "B"
      }
    }
  }, 
  "aggs": {
    "aGlobal": {
      "global": {},
      "aggs": {
        "aTerm": {
          "terms": {
            "field": "aField.keyword",
            "size": 10
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

It should return
```
(...)
"aggregations" : {
    "aGlobal" : {
      "doc_count" : 3,
      "aTerm" : {
        "doc_count_error_upper_bound" : 0,
        "sum_other_doc_count" : 0,
        "buckets" : [
          {
            "key" : "B",
            "doc_count" : 2
          },
          {
            "key" : "A",
            "doc_count" : 1
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
(...)
```
but instead we get (the only difference being  "profile": "true" set in the request)
```
(...)
 "aggregations" : {
    "aGlobal" : {
      "doc_count" : 2,
      "aTerm" : {
        "doc_count_error_upper_bound" : 0,
        "sum_other_doc_count" : 0,
        "buckets" : [
          {
            "key" : "B",
            "doc_count" : 2
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  },
(...)
```

